@1bfqutudhtexlka, in general, you need at least one peer with an open port, to be able to publish data on ZeroNet and that's also a requirement for PeerMessage.

@moor, the stream is captured through the [`mediaDevices`-API](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/MediaDevices/getUserMedia) (IIRC), which I believe returns an object that, in the case of StreamZ gets converted (I guess "or encoded") to a base64-string. That base64-piece then gets sent to the peers (together with some other information, e.g. the ID of the piece).
As PeerMessage doesn't support a continous stream of data (I think), StreamZ uses the "delay"-setting when you set up a stream to split the data into pieces each as long as defined by delay. Then the ID gets assigned which is basically just the index of that piece of the whole stream. To counter stuttering when switching to the newly received video (because it has to load a bit at first), we use two players that alternate playing the videos. So having a too short delay might also be bad as I noted before because it might mean that the watching browser works more to load the pieces than to play them.

I don't actually remember if we discussed using a different method for encoding the data tho, and I can only assume that the technique we implemented for StreamZ is somewhat "unique" as opposed to other streaming platforms, because we don't actually use a continous stream (if I am correct in that statement ofc).

